  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">FTF Bangladesh Horticulture, Fruits and Non-food Crops Activity</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">(Bangladesh):  The Horticulture, Fruits and Non-food Crops activity will support the Government of Bangladesh&apos;s food security objective by increasing the private sector&apos;s capacity to increase productivity and production of quality horticulture, fruits, and non-food crops that meet international standards.  The activity will also strengthen the value chain, linking Bangladeshi smallholder commercial farmers and other value chain actors, thereby increasing the efficiency of the market system to meet domestic and international market demands.  This will result in a more competitive private sector and efficient market systems that will increase farmers&apos; income and improve food security of Bangladesh.  It will also increase the export potential of fruits, vegetables, and non-food-crops to regional and domestic markets, thereby increasing the ability of Bangladesh to earn foreign exchange for its development purposes.The activity will contribute to achieving the three objectives of the Global Food Security Strategy and the Indo-Pacific Strategy through trade and competitiveness by increasing private sector engagement to bring additional financial and technical tools and expertise to the FTF development portfolio.  The activity will further contribute to actualizing the Agency&apos;s Journey to Self-Reliance.  In response to COVID-19, the activity will strengthen or re-establish local markets by investing in key value chains; support mechanization and labor saving methods, due to potential labor shortages; identify other opportunities to increase the financial resilience of small and medium enterprises in the agri-food system to improve their ability to weather this shock; and leverage existing information dissemination programs to share critical COVID-19 messages.  This activity supports the U.S. government&apos;s mission objectives of improved food security, and increased fair and reciprocal trade and investment..</narrative>
  </description>
